template:about.title: About
template:about.text: About Ember addon that provides a component which uses Google Places API to autocomplete place information when someone writes an address in a text field. It gives you all the information of a place from Google. You can do whatever you want with that information using a callback function or using the service functions. This addon provides two strategies to be able to communicate with Google place autocomplete services. place-autocomplete-field component This component is a input text field that fetches Google place predictions while the user is typing. More information: here google-place-autocomplete service Instead of using the standard Google place autocomplete component, which delegates to google the responsibility of adding the UI elements to intereact with place predictions. It is possible to use a Google service that you can call to get the information in JSON format. The service provides more flexibility when communicating with Google Places API. One advantage of usin the service is the possibility to use sessionTokens in order to reduce the cost of paid services when getting places information. More information: here Issues You can report any issue you find here

template:docs/addon-tests/mocks.title: Test Mocks
template:docs/addon-tests/mocks.text: Test Mocks When writting acceptance tests for parts of an application that interact with place-autocomplete-field or the service, it will be needed to mock Google's Autocomplete. The before each function of your acceptance/integration test is a good place to do it. This addon provides a mocked Google response . The following example shows how to use the Mock with a Mocha as testing framework. import { describe, it } from 'mocha'; import { expect } from 'chai'; import { GooglePlaceAutocompleteMockedObject } from 'ember-place-autocomplete/test-support'; it("does something", async function() { // Mock only google places window.google.maps.__gjsload__ = function() { return true; }; window.google.maps.places.Autocomplete = GooglePlaceAutocompleteMockedObject; const fakeModel = EmberObject.create({ address: 'fake address'}); // expects something expect(this.get('fakeModel.address')).to.equal('fake address'); });

template:docs/configuration.title: Configuration
template:docs/configuration.text: Configuration Options The following information is to add additional configurations, like adding a Google API Key or Client ID. In order to supply a Google API key or client ID, or choose to exclude the Google API, etc. Add the supported configuration instructions in the config/environment.js as the following example shows. ... ENV['place-autocomplete'] = { exclude: true, key: 'AIZ...', client: 'gme-myclientid', version: 3.27, // Optional - if client is set version must be above 3.24 language: 'en', // Optional - be default will be based on your browser language region: 'GB', // Optional contentForType: 'head' // Optional - Specifies which content-for tag the script will be injected into, defaults to 'head' }; ... Content Security Policy When using ember-cli-content-security-policy, it is required to add google maps to the application allowed sources /* More code here */ contentSecurityPolicy: { 'default-src': "'none'", 'script-src': "'self' 'unsafe-eval' *.googleapis.com maps.gstatic.com", 'font-src': "'self' fonts.gstatic.com", 'connect-src': "'self' maps.gstatic.com", 'img-src': "'self' *.googleapis.com maps.gstatic.com csi.gstatic.com data:", 'style-src': "'self' 'unsafe-inline' fonts.googleapis.com maps.gstatic.com assets-cdn.github.com" }, /* More code here */

template:docs/installation.title: Installation
template:docs/installation.text: Installation Go to the Ember project directory in the console and run the following command. It will add the addon to the package.json dependencies. ember install ember-place-autocomplete

template:docs/usage/component.title: How to use as component
template:docs/usage/component.text: How to use as component When there is only a need to have an autocomplete text field to find an address, it is possible to use this component to enable all the power of Google. Google provides further documentation about what is happening behind the scenes here Basic usage The following example shows how to use the place autocomplete field with a place change callback function and a on blur callback function. This example assumes two actions are defined in the controller: done and placeChanged. The usage of model.address assumes that the current route loads an object with a property address, which is going to be set using the callback function provided. Model address: Autocompletion could stop working on this example, because it uses a GOOGLE API KEY with limited number of request per day. Google response Component usage with restrictions This place autocomplete field only returns places from Colombia. It happens because a restrictions object is being passed to the component using the restrictions property. Model address: Autocompletion could stop working on this example, because it uses a GOOGLE API KEY with limited number of request per day. Google response import Controller from '@ember/controller'; export default Controller.extend({ init() { this._super(...arguments); this.setProperties({ googleAuto: null, restrictions: { country: 'co' } }); }, actions: { placeChangedSecondInput(place){ this.set('placeJSONSecondInput', JSON.stringify(place, undefined, 2)); } } }); Component options Option Param type Description onBlurCallback String/action Name of the function or function that is going to be executed after focus out in the address input placeChangedCallback String/action Name of the function or function that is going to be executed when address changed inputClass String CSS class for the input. types String featured types separate by comma describing the given result, for more info here restrictions Object Example. { country: "us" }, more info here placeIdOnly Boolean Defaults to false, only fetches the Place ID when calling the Google Places API, more information can be found here withGeoLocate Boolean It allows searching places near by the coordinates given into browser. more info See attribute options.bounds setValueWithProperty String Name of the property returned by Google to set the input field value after selection. More info about properties available here latLngBounds Object Ex. {sw: {lat: -34, lng: 151}, ne: {lat: -33, lng: 152}}, It allows searching places near by the given coordinates. More info See attribute options.bounds preventSubmit Boolean Ex. true, allows to prevent the form to be submitted if the user selects a location and hit ENTER value Object Model property where the address is going to be stored. It is recommended to avoid using this propoerty and use the placeChangedCallback to set the value to the desired property Details about the PlaceChangedCallback option This function is going to receive a javascript object with the response from Google Places API (Response details). You can use the information as you wish. In order to prevent double binding, it is possible to don't use the value and set the value using the action passed here. template:docs/usage/service.title: How to use as service
template:docs/usage/service.text: How to use as service Sometimes there is not need to get the full information of a place everytime a user types a word inside the input, that is why this service exists. This service interacts with the Google Place Autocomplete API and uses benefits like the usage of the sessionToken. The sessionToken is useful to reduce the cost of using the Google Places API. Official information about this topic is available here If you want to know more about the Google Place Autocomplete service, read about it here Example The following example of service usage creates an input field that mimics the functionality of the input field provided by this addon. In order to have a better example, ember-power-select is used to have a better input text an get cross browser compatibility for free. For more information about ember-power-select go here. Autocompletion could stop working on this example, because it uses a GOOGLE API KEY with limited number of request per day Google response import Controller from '@ember/controller'; import { inject as service } from '@ember/service'; import { isBlank } from '@ember/utils'; import { next } from '@ember/runloop'; export default Controller.extend({ googlePlaceAutocompleteService: service('google-place-autocomplete'), async _getPlaceDetails(placeId) { let googleRequest = { placeId: placeId, fields: ['address_components', 'formatted_address', 'place_id', 'rating'] }; let placeDetails = await this.get('googlePlaceAutocompleteService').getDetails(googleRequest); this._refreshPrettyResponse(placeDetails); }, _refreshPrettyResponse(placeDetails) { this.set('placeServiceResultJSON', null); next(() => { this.set('placeServiceResultJSON', JSON.stringify(placeDetails, undefined, 2)); }); }, actions: { findPlaceDetails(selectedPlace) { if (isBlank(selectedPlace)) { this.setProperties({ selectedPlace: null, predictions: [], placeServiceResultJSON: null }); return; } this._getPlaceDetails(selectedPlace.place_id); this.setProperties({ selectedPlace: selectedPlace, predictions: [] }); }, async requestPredictions(placeServiceInput) { if (isBlank(placeServiceInput)) { this.setProperties({ predictions: [], placeServiceResultJSON: null }); } let properties = { input: placeServiceInput }; let predictions = await this.get('googlePlaceAutocompleteService').getPlacePredictions(properties); this.set('predictions', predictions); } } }); Google response; Available functions Function Return getPlacePredictions Promise getQueryPredictions Promise getDetails Promise updateSessionToken Void
